Executive Summary
The Transient Supra-Coherence (TSC) operator, designated T-U°, is a formally derived,
empirically validated measure of instantaneous multi-layer representational alignment in
autonomous systems governed by the Absolute(0) Stability Framework (ASV3-FORMAL). This
white paper presents the complete theoretical foundations, formal guarantees, and empirical
evidence for the TSC operator and its associated hyper-coherence phenomenon.
At its core, TSC answers a single operational question at every governance step: how coherent
are the system's internal representations across all layers, relative to its control inputs and future
trajectory? A high TSC value certifies that layer states, the gradient correction kernel, and the
future-adjacency vector are mutually aligned — a condition termed hyper-coherence — and that
governance coupling should be correspondingly tightened.
Empirical validation across 80 benchmark runs (state-space dimensions d ∈ {64, 128, 256, 512,
1024}, four signal regimes, four defence domains, 500 steps each) confirms: zero invariant
violations universally, 100% anchor lock across all conditions, and peak TSC values of 1.639 at
d = 1024 under adversarial loading. Under adversarial conditions, the system spends 78.4% of
operating time in the T-U° hyper-coherent regime — the highest-performance governance
configuration.
