2. Theoretical Foundations
2.1 The Taleken–Völundr Framework
The broader theoretical context for the TSC operator is the Taleken–Völundr framework, a
spectral admissibility engine that maintains the system state within a spectrally regular manifold
via event-triggered gradient correction. The framework is grounded in a spectral observable
algebra computed from the governed state x ∈ X ⊆ ℝᵈ
.
The central object is the Taleken concentration metric Δ(t), defined as the deviation of the spectral
kurtosis from its admissibility threshold. The system is spectrally admissible if and only if Δ(t) ≤ 0.
When Δ(t) > 0, the Taleken–Völundr Law triggers event-driven gradient correction, directing the
system back toward the admissible manifold via the AGGL correction field.
Crucially, this correction field is the source of the ultra-kernel u★ that feeds into TSC. During
active Taleken correction, u★ is non-zero and large, elevating TSC(t) and potentially driving the
system into the hyper-coherent regime. TSC thus converts an active governance response into a
positive coherence signal, creating a virtuous feedback loop between admissibility enforcement
and representational alignment.
