The TSC operator is defined over the state space X ⊆ ℝᵈ, where d is the state-space dimension.
All vectors are elements of ℝᵈ with the standard Euclidean norm.
Dimension-Normalised Layer Norm
For a layer-state vector s ∈ ℝᵈ, the dimension-normalised norm is:
λ(s) = ‖s‖ / (√d + ε)
where ε > 0 is a small regularisation constant. The normalisation by √d renders λ dimension-
independent in expectation for unit-variance inputs, enabling meaningful coherence comparisons
across architecture instantiations of different depths and widths.
TSC Functional
Given layer states L = {s₁, …, sₙ} ⊂ ℝᵈ, ultra-kernel u ∈ ℝᵈ, and future-adjacency vector f ∈ ℝᵈ:
Φ = Σᵢ λ(sᵢ) [layer superposition norm]
u★ = λ(u) [ultra-kernel norm]
sτ = λ(f) · min(τf, 2) [future-adjacency norm]
TSC(t) = (Φ + u★ + sτ) / (n + 2)
The denominator (n + 2) normalises by the total number of signal components — n governance
layers plus the ultra-kernel and future-adjacency — ensuring TSC(t) is a per-component average
comparable across systems with different numbers of governance layers.
GREEN-Phase Coherence Amplification
When the governance phase is GREEN and the current session is valid, TSC(t) receives a 1.05×
multiplicative boost. This reflects the empirical observation that GREEN-phase coherence is more
predictive of sustained stability than coherence achieved during recovery from RED. A system
maintaining continuous admissibility has demonstrated a higher quality of governance — the
boost rewards this distinction, creating a measurable coherence premium for sustained nominal
operation.
