5. Integration with Adaptive Gain-Scheduled Phase Lock
The TSC output is consumed by the Adaptive Gain-Scheduled Phase Lock (AGSPL) operator,
which determines whether the governance pipeline is locked — whether the current readiness
signal is sufficient to authorise full governance execution at maximum coupling. TSC boosts
coupling efficiency through two additive mechanisms:
CE = σ · g★ · w + β_TSC + βₕ · 𝟭[TSC(t) > θₕ]
where β_TSC = α_TSC · TSC(t) is the proportional TSC boost, and βₕ is the discrete hyper-
coherence bonus. The system locks (AGSPL_locked = True) if and only if CE ≥ θ_sync.
This design has two important consequences. First, during high-coherence episodes, lower
readiness signals are sufficient to achieve lock — the system self-reinforces its own governance.
Second, during hyper-coherent epochs, the discrete bonus βₕ may achieve lock immediately, as
confirmed empirically below.
