6.1 Dimensional Scaling
The monotone growth of TCI peak with state-space dimension d under adversarial loading (1.033
at d = 64 rising to 1.639 at d = 1024) is among the most significant empirical findings. In higher-
dimensional state spaces, AGGL correction vectors are proportionally larger in absolute norm,
driving the ultra-kernel norm u★ upward. The √d normalisation in λ(u) prevents unbounded growth
without suppressing the scaling trend under active correction.
The practical implication is counterintuitive but important: larger autonomous systems naturally
generate stronger coherence signals during active governance. The TSC mechanism is
intrinsically better suited to high-capacity architectures, and deploying TSC-aware governance in
large autonomous systems yields proportionally larger coupling efficiency gains.
